
findcommand
1. What is find?
find is used to search for files and directories in a directory hierarchy.

It can search based on:

name
type
size
time
permissions
owner/group
and perform actions using -exec
It is one of the most powerful and essential Linux commands.


2. Basic Syntax
find <starting_directory> <conditions> <actions>

Example:

find /home/user -name "file.txt"

Search starts from /home/user and looks for the file.


3. Search by File Name
3.1 Search by exact name
find . -name "file.txt"

Searches for exactly file.txt in the current directory and subdirectories.

Output example
./notes/file.txt


3.2 Case-insensitive name search
find . -iname "file.txt"

Matches:

file.txt
File.txt
FILE.TXT
FiLe.TxT
Output example
./Docs/File.txt


3.3 Search by partial name (wildcards)
find . -name "*.log"

Finds all files ending with .log.

find . -name "data*"

Finds files that start with data.


4. Search by Type
File types:
f → regular file
d → directory
l → symbolic link
c → character device
b → block device
4.1 Find only files
find . -type f


4.2 Find only directories
find . -type d


4.3 Find symbolic links
find . -type l


5. Search by Size
Supported units:
c → bytes
k → kilobytes
M → megabytes
G → gigabytes
Operators:
+ → greater than
- → smaller than
no sign → exact size

5.1 Files larger than 10 MB
find . -size +10M


5.2 Files smaller than 500 KB
find . -size -500k


5.3 Files exactly 100 bytes
find . -size 100c


6. Search by Modified Time
mtime → modification time (days)
mmin → modification time (minutes)

Signs meaning:
+ → more than
- → less than
no sign → exactly

6.1 Files modified in last 1 day
find . -mtime -1


6.2 Files modified more than 7 days ago
find . -mtime +7


6.3 Files modified exactly 2 days ago
find . -mtime 2


6.4 Files modified in last 30 minutes
find . -mmin -30


6.5 Files modified more than 2 hours ago
find . -mmin +120


7. Search by Permissions
7.1 Search files with 777 permission
find . -perm 777


7.2 Search files writable by group
find . -perm -g=w


7.3 Search executables
find . -perm -111

Meaning: owner, group, and others all have execute permission.


8. Search by Owner or Group
8.1 Files owned by user
find . -user sai


8.2 Files belonging to group
find . -group developers


9. Search Empty Files and Folders
9.1 Empty files
find . -type f -empty


9.2 Empty directories
find . -type d -empty


10. Exclude Certain Paths
find . -path "./node_modules/*" -prune -o -name "*.js" -print

Explanation:

Skips node_modules
Finds .js files elsewhere

11. Running Commands on Found Files (-exec)
The most important feature.

Format:

-exec command {} \;

Here:

{} = file found
\; = end of command

11.1 Delete files
find . -name "*.tmp" -exec rm {} \;


11.2 Delete empty files
find . -type f -empty -exec rm {} \;


11.3 Delete empty directories
find . -type d -empty -exec rmdir {} \;


11.4 Change permissions of found files
find . -type f -name "*.sh" -exec chmod +x {} \;


11.5 View file details with ls -l
find . -name "*.conf" -exec ls -l {} \;

Example Output
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 203 /etc/nginx/nginx.conf


12. -exec vs -execdir
-exec
Runs command in the current directory.

-execdir
Runs command in the file’s directory.

Example:

find . -name "*.log" -execdir rm {} \;

More secure for deletion actions.


13. Multiple Conditions (AND, OR)
AND (default)
find . -type f -name "*.log" -size +1M

OR
find . \( -name "*.txt" -o -name "*.md" \)


14. Printing Only Filenames
find . -name "*.txt" -print

-print is automatic if no action is given.


15. Using find with xargs (Faster Performance)
find . -name "*.log" | xargs rm

Deletes files faster than -exec.


16. Real-World Examples
16.1 Find large log files (>100MB)
find /var/log -type f -size +100M


16.2 Find files modified today
find . -mtime 0


16.3 Find all Python files and list details
find . -name "*.py" -exec ls -l {} \;


16.4 Find and zip each file
find . -name "*.txt" -exec gzip {} \;


16.5 Find files not accessed in last 10 days
find . -atime +10


Summary
The find command is one of the most powerful tools in Linux.
It can search by name, type, size, time, permissions, ownership, and more.
With -exec, it can perform actions on found files, making it essential for automation and administration.

